04214nam a22005295i 9780774850490DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20072003xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748504907 a10.59962/97807748504902doi  a(DE-B1597)662292  a(OCoLC)951200225  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aD769.87.A4 ǂb P47 2003eb 7aHIS0271102bisacsh04a940.54/281 aPerras, Galen, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aStepping Stones to Nowhere :bThe Aleutian Islands, Alaska, and American Military Strategy, 1867-1945 /cGalen Perras. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[2007] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (288 p.) :b14 b&w photos, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tMaps and Illustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAbbreviations -- tOne of Our Great Strategic Points -- tHe Who Holds Alaska Will Hold the World -- tEntirely Open to Attack -- tAll Commanders on Minor Fronts Regard Their Own Actions As Highly Important -- tTotal Destruction Is the Only Answer -- tA Strong Alaska Means a Foot-Loose Fleet -- tWe Have Opened the Door to Tokyo -- tStepping Stones to Nowhere -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Aleutian Islands, a mostly forgotten portion of the United States on the southwest coast of Alaska, have often assumed a key role in American military strategy. W.H. Seward, the US secretary of state who brokered the purchase of Alaska, believed that the acquisition would permit the United States to dominate the Pacific. In the 1990s, Bill Clinton attempted to install an American ballistic missile defence system on the islands. But for most Americans, prior to the Second World War, the bleak and barren islands were of far less interest than the Philippines. In Stepping Stones to Nowhere, Galen Perras shows how that changed with the Japanese occupation of the western Aleutians, which climaxed in the horrendous battle for Attu. Efforts to make the area a major theatre of war rivalling Europe or the South Pacific foundered, but certainly not for lack of effort. The campaign was unique in its involvement of Britain, the Soviet Union, and Canada. Perras reveals how this clash in the North Pacific demonstrated serious problems with the way that American civilian and military decision makers sought to incite a global conflict. Thoroughly researched and accessible, this book will be invaluable to military and naval historians as well as those with a general interest in the history of the Second World War.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Military / United States.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000z978311141860540uhttps://doi.org/10.59962/978077485049040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780774850490423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780774850490/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  a978-3-11-141860-5  University of British Columbia eBook-Package 2013-2000c2013d2000  aGBV-deGruyter-alles